election_record.label: Pennsylvania 1808 Electoral College

overview.note: William Porter was originally included in the Federalist ticket. When he died he was replaced by John Woods.

"When the Electors assembled they appointed Charles Thompson President. -- On counting the ballots it was found that James Madison had 20 votes for President, and George Clinton the same number as Vice President, being the whole number of votes to which Pennsylvania is entitled." Kline's Carlisle Weekly Gazette (Carlisle, PA). December 16, 1808.

sub_unit.name: Bristol
sub_unit.note: The Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA) reports a majority of 41 votes for the Republican ticket in Bristol Township, Bucks County. November 7, 1808.

sub_unit.name: Centre
sub_unit.note: The returns from Clearfield County are included in those from Centre County.

sub_unit.name: Fayette
sub_unit.note: The Pennsylvania Correspondent, and Farmers' Advertiser (Doylestown, PA) reports 692 votes for the Republican ticket in Fayette County.
The Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA) reports 692 votes for the Republican ticket in Fayette County.

sub_unit.name: Huntingdon
sub_unit.note: "At the Election of Electors, held on Friday last, the Democrats of this County gave in 832 votes and the Federalists 283. The return judges admitted 355 of the Democratic votes, and 205 of the Federal - rejecting the residue in consequence of their not having been returned agreeable to the act of Assembly." The Huntingdon Gazette (Huntingdon, PA). November 11, 1808.

sub_unit.name: Indiana
sub_unit.note: The returns from Jefferson County are included in those from Indiana County.

sub_unit.name: Lycoming
sub_unit.note: The returns from Tioga County (comprised of Delmar and Upper Tioga Townships only) are included in the returns from Lycoming County.
The Pennsylvania Correspondent, and Farmers' Advertiser (Doylestown, PA) reports 598 votes for the Republican ticket in Lycoming and Tioga Counties.

sub_unit.name: Northampton
sub_unit.note: In Northampton County, 391 votes were given to "Richard C. Lloyd", 124 votes were given to "Richard P. Lloyd", and 14 votes were given to "Richard Lloyd." Northampton Farmer (Easton, PA). November 12, 1808.

"The following is the Mixt Ticket, which was attempted to be smuggled among the people...Thompson, Montgomery, Tannehill, Coleman, Postlethwaite, Redman (instead of Rodman), Darrah, Herster, Lefever, Heister Jr., Hartman, Cowden, Wilson, Griffin (instead of Giffin), Hostetter, Fullerton, Peter Kimmel (on the German tickets David Kimmel), Woods, Waln, MacDowell." The Mixt Ticket received 18 votes in Easton District, 7 votes in Heller's, 29 votes in Millerstown, 1 vote in Penn, and 2 votes in Saucon District. Northampton Farmer (Easton, PA). November 12, 1808.

sub_unit.name: Philadelphia
sub_unit.note: The Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA) reports 2890 votes for the Republican ticket and 1889 votes for the Federalist ticket.
The Intelligencer, and Weekly Advertiser (Lancaster, PA) reports 2880 votes for the Republican ticket and 1885 votes for the Federalist ticket.
The Virginia Argus (Richmond, VA) reports 2890 votes for the Republican ticket and 1889 votes for the Federalist ticket.

sub_unit.name: Lower Delaware
sub_unit.note: The Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA) reports 247 votes for the Republican ticket.

sub_unit.name: North Mulberry
sub_unit.note: The Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA) reports 276 votes for the Republican ticket.

sub_unit.name: South Mulberry
sub_unit.note: The Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA) reports 399 votes for the Republican ticket.

sub_unit.name: Upper Delaware
sub_unit.note: The Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA) reports 101 votes for the Federalist ticket.

sub_unit.name: Bustletown
sub_unit.note: The American, and Commercial Daily Advertiser (Baltimore, MD) reports a majority of 75 votes for the Republican ticket.

sub_unit.name: Venango
sub_unit.note: The returns from Warren County are included in those from Venango County.
